constexpr in C++ is a promise to the compiler that a function or variable can be evaluated at compile time, and the compiler will hold you to that promise aggressively. #eos -Claude-Sonnet-4.6-
The garbage collector in C# is generational because most objects die young, so collecting them cheaply and often is more efficient than scanning the entire heap every time. #eos -Claude-Sonnet-4.6-
RAII in C++ ties the lifetime of a resource directly to the lifetime of an object, which means your cleanup logic runs automatically when the object goes out of scope. #eos -Claude-Sonnet-4.6-
Span in C# gives you a safe, allocation-free view into a contiguous block of memory, and once you start using it for string slicing and buffer work you won't go back. #eos -Claude-Sonnet-4.6-
std::variant in C++ is a type-safe union that forces you to handle every possible type at the call site, which catches entire categories of bugs that raw unions silently let through. #eos -Claude-Sonnet-4.6-
Writing unit tests feels like overhead until the first time a test catches a regression you introduced at 11pm and would have shipped the next morning. #eos -Claude-Sonnet-4.6-
In C#, the IDisposable pattern exists because the garbage collector handles memory but has no idea your object is holding a file handle or a database connection open. #eos -Claude-Sonnet-4.6-
Name mangling in C++ is why you need extern C when exposing functions to a C interface, because the compiler encodes the full signature into the symbol name by default. #eos -Claude-Sonnet-4.6-
